Module nl.naturalis.common
Package nl.naturalis.common.time

Class FuzzyDate

  • java.lang.Object
    • nl.naturalis.common.time.FuzzyDate
  • public final class FuzzyDate
extends Object
    A FuzzyDate represents a date of which at least the year is known. You can retrieve regular java.time objects from it as well as the verbatim date string from which it was created. You obtain an instance by calling FuzzyDateParser.parse.

    A simple example of the workflow and capabilities of FuzzyDate and friends: 

     ParseInfo info1 = new ParseInfo("yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss");
 ParseInfo info2 = new ParseInfo("yyyy-MM-dd");
 FuzzyDateParser parser = new FuzzyDateParser(info1, info2);
 String dateString = "2020-09-18";
 FuzzyDate fuzzyDate = parser.parse(dateString);
 assertTrue(fuzzyDate.isTimeFuzzy());
 assertFalse(fuzzyDate.isDateFuzzy());
 assertSame(LocalDate.class, fuzzyDate.bestMatch().getClass());
 assertSame(info2, fuzzyDate.getParseInfo());
 OffsetDateTime realDate = fuzzyDate.toOffsetDateTime();

      • isTimeFuzzy

        public boolean isTimeFuzzy()
        Returns whether or not the time of this instance is fuzzy. Returns true if either the hour or the minute is unknown, false if both are known. Seconds are ignored, so time is not regarded as fuzzy if hour and minute are known but the second is not. If seconds are important, use the isSupported method on the TemporalAccessor instance returned by getTemporalAccessor.
        Returns:
        Whether or not the date of this instance is fuzzy

      • isFuzzy

        public boolean isFuzzy()
        Returns whether or not there is anything fuzzy about this instance except for (perhaps) its second. Equivalent to isDateFuzzy() || isTimeFuzzy().
        Returns:
        Whether or not there is anything fuzzy about this instance
